1. Network overview

Let’s get an idea of the school network. Here I am using the data from the file “edgelist.csv”, where I have directed nominations for 2 categories: “good friends” and “best friends”. I build 2 networks: 1 for “good friends” (Amistad = 1), and one for “best friends” (Amistad = 2). Below, I plot the 2 networks and summarize the main properties in a table and in 3 histograms.

2. Analyses on participants who are in the experiment

We now examine the network metrics for participants in the experiment. It may also be useful to compare different methods for computing these metrics.

Another thing to note is that the distribution of eigenvector centrality contains individuals with high values (EC or BC), which may affect the results.

In other words, differences in network metrics may not directly correspond to differences in appropriateness ratings as a function of these metrics.

Good friends network

Best Friends Network

3. Regression analyses of appropriateness of violation/punishment of violation

Using the above mentioned network metrics as independent variables, I will not explore weather they predict any difference in the appropriate ratings for both violations and punishment of violations, in the two treatments (friends vs. non-friends).

I will start with a simple regression of rating ~ [network metric].

I will use both metrics from the “good-friends” and the “best-friends” social networks. In-degree metrics were standardized for easier interpretation.

3.1 Appropriateness ratings by network measures

The only significant predictors of ratings are in-degree and eigenvector centrality, both with a positive effect. This shows that participants who are more central rate violations as more appropriate.

3.2 Appropriateness ratings by network measures and treatment

I know include treatment (friend vs. non-friend) as an interaction in the regression model. We again see a main effect of … and a main effect of treatment, as we saw in the analyses without network propertis.

This means that ratings of approppriateness of a violation of a friend vs. a non-friend were not related with the centrality of the rater.

4 Punishment

We now turn to the appropriateness of punishment. Remember here that the rater is not the one punishing, but rather they are rating how appropriate it is for a friend, to punish a friend/non-friends.

Vizualization of main regression results

Showing the most interesting results across all regressions

Violation rating ~ In-degree

The higher participants’ in degree, the higher the appropriateness rating. Ratings are averaged across the 5 domain for each participants: Each dot is 1 participant in 1 treatment (nf = non-friend, f = friend)

Violation rating ~ Eigenvector Centrality

The higher participants’ in degree, the higher the appropriateness rating. Ratings are averaged across the 5 domain for each participants: Each dot is 1 participant in 1 treatment (nf = non-friend, f = friend). Note that most participants are between 0 and 0.02
